{"cursor":"17095","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox University |name =Ghent University |native_name =Universiteit Gent\n(Dutch) |latin_name =Academia Gandavensis |image_name =UGent-\nLogo.jpg |motto =Audere Sapiens |mottoeng =Dare to Think |established =1817\n|type =Public |affiliation =Pluralistic |city =Ghent |state =Flanders |country\n=Belgium |coor = [http://www.ugent.be/en/ghentuniv/presentation Ghent University\nat a glance: facts and figures]. UGent. Retrieved February, 4 2010\n|students =38,000 \n[http://www.ugent.be/en/ghentuniv/presentation Ghent University at a glance:\nfacts and figures]. UGent. Retrieved February, 4 2010 |staff =7,100  |rector =Paul Van Cauwenberge \n[http://www.ugent.be/en/ghentuniv/administration/rector Ghent University central\nadministration â rector]. UGent. Retrieved February, 4 2010 |colours =Blue\nand Yellow |affiliations =Ghent University Association Santander Network\nErasmus Student Network European University Association CESAER\n|former_names =State University of Ghent (RUG) |website =http://www.ugent.be }}\n'Ghent University' (Dutch: 'Universiteit Gent', abbreviated as 'UGent') is a Dutch-\nspeaking public university located in Ghent, Belgium. It is one of the larger\nFlemish universities, consisting of 32,000 students and 7,100 staff members. The\ncurrent rector is Paul Van Cauwenberge.\n\nIt was established in 1817 by King William I of the Netherlands. After the\nBelgian revolution of 1830, it was administered by the newly formed Belgian\nstate. French became the academic language until 1930, when Ghent University\nbecame the first Dutch-speaking university in Belgium. In 1991, the university\nwas granted major autonomy and changed its name from State University of Ghent\n(Dutch: Rijksuniversiteit Gent, abbreviated as RUG) to its current name.\n","linknr":521,"url":"University_of_Ghent","recorded":1362374068,"links":55,"instances":["israel","academia"],"pdf":["http://www.globaluniversitiesrank